# AI Tools for LightSpeed Interns

Modern web development increasingly relies on AI tools to speed up coding, summarize information, manage design processes, and automate repetitive tasks. This guide lists required and recommended AI-powered apps, browser tools, and editor extensions LightSpeed interns should use, ensuring alignment with the Block Theme & Plugin Developer Internship.

Contents:

1. AI Chatbots & Assistants
2. Browser AI Assistants
3. AI-Related VS Code Extensions
4. Design System & Code-to-Design AI Integration
5. Tips for Using AI in Development
6. FAQ

---

## 1. AI Chatbots & Assistants

-   ChatGPT

    -   Purpose: Generative AI by OpenAI — text, speech, image generation; answers, brainstorming, code, translation, document summaries.
    -   How to access: Visit chat.openai.com, create account; install mobile apps from stores.
    -   Notes: Use Google account. Chrome extension available for search integration.

-   Claude (Anthropic)

    -   Purpose: AI assistant & code generator; advanced reasoning (Claude 3 family).
    -   How to access: Access via claude.ai; sign up with Google login optional.
    -   Notes: Use for research, brainstorming, summarization, code.

-   Gemini (Google AI)

    -   Purpose: Multimodal AI for language, code, image, audio, translation, design.
    -   How to access: Visit gemini.google.com with Google account; enable in Google AI Studio and Chrome DevTools.
    -   Notes: Use for writing assistance, code, doc analysis.

-   Brave Leo

    -   Purpose: AI assistant built into Brave Browser; privacy-focused summaries.
    -   How to access: Download Brave browser and enable Leo in sidebar.
    -   Notes: Works without account; supports several models.

-   NotebookLM

    -   Purpose: Gemini-powered research notebook; uploads PDFs/URLs/Docs/audio/video; summarizes with citations.
    -   How to access: Visit notebooklm.google.com and sign in with Google.
    -   Notes: Great for research, onboarding, and summarizing long docs.

-   Fireflies.ai

    -   Purpose: AI meeting/notes assistant — records, transcribes, summarizes action items.
    -   How to access: Install Chrome Extension; sign in with Google.
    -   Notes: Integrates with Google Calendar and Docs.

-   Loom
    -   Purpose: AI-powered screen recorder — generates video summaries, chapters, transcripts.
    -   How to access: Install desktop and Chrome extension; sign in with Google/Slack.
    -   Notes: Use for async demos and bug reports.

---

## 2. Browser AI Assistants

-   Chrome DevTools AI

    -   Purpose: Gemini-powered panel in DevTools for context-aware debugging, CSS/DOM analysis, code explanations, accessibility checks.
    -   How to enable: Open DevTools (F12), settings/experiments, enable AI Assistance.
    -   Notes: Excellent for debugging block themes and layouts.

-   Microsoft Edge Copilot

    -   Purpose: Microsoft AI assistant for in-browser explanations and summaries.
    -   How to enable: Download Edge, sign in, enable Copilot via browser icon.
    -   Notes: Great for code and content research.

-   Brave Leo
    -   Purpose: Integrated assistant for private summaries and content generation.
    -   How to enable: Enable via Brave sidebar.
    -   Notes: No account needed.

---

## 3. AI-Related VS Code Extensions

-   Claude Code (anthropic.claude-code) — Connects Claude model to VS Code: AI completion and editing for PHP/JS/config files.
-   Gemini Code Assist (google.geminicodeassist) — Google Gemini-powered code suggestions in VS Code.
-   GitHub Copilot (github.copilot) — Real-time AI pair programming, plus Copilot Chat.
-   Copilot Vision (ms-vscode.vscode-copilot-vision) — Adds vision/model diagram understanding to Copilot.
-   Codeium (codeium.codeium) — Multi-language AI code completion engine.
-   CodeRabbit (coderabbit.coderabbit-vscode) — AI code reviewer for explanations and refactors.
-   (Other suggested extension) Copilot Chat — Chat UI inside VS Code.

---

## 4. Design System & Code-to-Design AI Integration

Interns often use AI to:

-   Map Figma design tokens and variables to theme.json in WordPress.
-   Generate starter code and design assets via VS Code extensions.
-   Prompt block theme code/snippets directly from Figma using supported plugins.
-   Summarize design assets, patterns, or variable changes using built-in AI features in Figma.

Tools & plugins:

-   Figma MCP — "Model–Code–Prompt" for design-system-driven code generation. MCP is enabled on agency files for direct code/design syncing.
-   Figma AI Plugins — Search "AI" in Figma Community Plugins & add to account for mapping tokens/patterns and component usage help.

---

## 5. Tips for Using AI in Development

-   Be descriptive in prompts: Clearly state your code context and goal (e.g., "Generate a WordPress block for ...").
-   Always review AI output: Treat suggestions as drafts; test for correctness/security.
-   Respect privacy: Don’t share sensitive data (passwords, keys, private code) with any AI service.
-   Keep up-to-date: Watch LightSpeed announcements for recommended models and AI policy updates.

